Yes — a small CSS block will help apply that look on GitHub Pages or MkDocs.  
Here’s a lightweight snippet that mirrors your palette and spacing choices:

```css
/* Compassionate Chat visual theme snippet */

body {
  font-family: 'Nunito', 'Open Sans', sans-serif;
  background-color: #FAFAFA;
  color: #333333;
  line-height: 1.6;
  margin: 1.5rem auto;
  max-width: 900px;
  padding: 0 1rem;
}

/* Headings */
h1, h2, h3 {
  font-family: 'Lato', 'Open Sans', sans-serif;
  color: #4CAF50;         /* primary accent */
  margin-top: 2rem;
}

/* Secondary headings or info banners */
h4, h5 {
  color: #42A5F5;         /* secondary accent */
}

/* Divider lines and subtle section boxes */
hr {
  border: 0;
  border-top: 2px solid #E0E0E0;
  margin: 2rem 0;
}

/* Emphasis links */
a {
  color: #1976D2;
  text-decoration: none;
}
a:hover {
  text-decoration: underline;
}

/* Optional tagline styling */
.tagline {
  color: #2E7D32;
  font-style: italic;
  font-weight: 600;
}
```

Save it as `compassionate-chat.css` and include the link in your Markdown or MkDocs config.  
